{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17532535","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17532535"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:27:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:27:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14686"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14686","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14686"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.3,0.06,0.5,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7379"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57995"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7379","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7379"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14686"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43454"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18015"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57995","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57995"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with three months of progressive shortness of breath on exertion. She now becomes breathless after walking 100 metres on flat ground. She has also experienced two episodes of dizziness when climbing stairs. She has a history of hypertension and osteoarthritis. Her medications include amlodipine and paracetamol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 76/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Cardiac examination reveals a harsh ejection systolic murmur, loudest at the right upper sternal border with radiation to the carotids. The murmur increases with squatting and decreases with standing. Chest examination is otherwise normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn echocardiogram shows calcified aortic valve leaflets with reduced mobility, peak velocity 4.8 m/s, mean gradient 52 mmHg, and valve area 0.8 cm2. Left ventricular ejection fraction is 55%.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Medical therapy with beta blockers","Balloon valvuloplasty","Exercise stress testing","Urgent valve replacement","Annual clinical review"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptomatic severe aortic stenosis, as evidenced by exertional dyspnoea and pre-syncope, along with confirmatory echocardiogram findings (peak velocity \u0026gt;4 m/s, mean gradient \u0026gt;40 mmHg, valve area \u0026lt;1.0 cm2). The presence of symptoms in severe aortic stenosis indicates a poor prognosis without intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent valve replacement\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management. Once symptoms develop in severe aortic stenosis, the average survival without intervention is 2-3 years. Either surgical aortic valve replacement (SAVR) or transcatheter aortic valve implantation (TAVI) would be considered, with the choice depending on surgical risk and patient factors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnnual clinical review\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for asymptomatic severe aortic stenosis. However, once symptoms develop, urgent intervention is required due to the high risk of sudden cardiac death.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMedical therapy with beta blockers\u003C/strong\u003E has no role in altering the natural history of aortic stenosis. While beta blockers may be used to treat coexisting conditions, they do not prevent progression of valve disease or improve survival.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExercise stress testing\u003C/strong\u003E is useful in patients with severe aortic stenosis who deny symptoms or have equivocal symptoms. In this case, the patient has clear symptoms, making stress testing unnecessary and potentially dangerous.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBalloon valvuloplasty\u003C/strong\u003E is rarely used as a definitive treatment for aortic stenosis in adults due to high recurrence rates. It may be considered as a bridge to definitive valve replacement in critically ill patients or for palliation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Severe aortic stenosis with symptoms requires urgent valve replacement.","Classic symptoms of severe aortic stenosis are exertional dyspnoea, angina, and syncope.","The presence of symptoms in severe aortic stenosis indicates poor prognosis without intervention."],"references":["2021 ESC/EACTS Guidelines for the management of valvular heart disease"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43454"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14686"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43454","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43454"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-28T19:20:58+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-28T19:22:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7379"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57995"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"C